description.text: Roll ball bearings down the inclined ramp to launch them into orbits around a central potential. Teaching materials appropriate for all levels (orbits_description.tex and orbits_description.pdf) as well as the MATLAB code (orbits_3dprinting.m) used to generate this surface are available as well.

Coarse resolution (0.3mm / fast), Raft ON, Support OFF, PLA plastic, two shells, 3% infill. Higher infills may be used for a sturdier structure. To use a 0.5" diameter stanless steel ball bearing, print to a size 75 mm high, and 50 mm x 50 mm wide.

title: Simple modular x-end for Prusa (lm8uu bearings)

description.text: A simple, extensible x-end for a Prusa v2 or any similarly designed machine. I grew tired of overly specific parts and have started breaking them down into easy to print components that can be upgraded or replaced piece by piece. The included z-float is inspired by the wobble arrestors which were one of the best upgrades I ever made to my Cupcake and they work admirably to decouple a Pruza z-axis. These are inspired by: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18384 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15492

For each x-end you will require two of the modular_x-end.stl. If you find it too flexible, print the rigid version instead. Print 2 of the x-ends, flip one upside down and screw them together with m3 screws/nuts.
The completed assembly should clamp down tightly around the x smooth rods.
lm8uu bearings should easily fit, if not, adjust the scad until you are happy. If they are a bit loose you can try a cable tie around the holder to keep them in place. Print 1 of the z-floats for each x-end. The attached float will work with any leadscrew that has a m8 sized nut (eg m8 threaded rod or certain acme leadscrews). If you want to change leadscrews, leave the x-end in place and print a new holder of your own design. The float can go above or below the x-end, I find it looks a little cleaner below. The idler bracket included works with 2 608 bearings sandwiched between 2 m8 washers. A single sided idler bracket should work just as well but I find the crude reinforcement of the box shape helps resist flexion. I have not yet included the matching motor bracket but will do so once I've tested it a bit. If you want to create your own idler/motor brackets or any other attachments, the mounting holes are sized for m3 screws spaced 15mm apart (along x). The two rows of three screws should be separated by 25mm when the two halves of the assembly are joined.

Two color customizable necktie. Customize the size and pattern. No dual extruders needed and it is semi-flexible!

TO GET PROPER STLs: Set all the design parameters first. Then turn off the "Preview all" option and click "Create Thing" once with the "Pattern Pieces" option selected AND click it again with the "Tie Body" option selected. Customizer will spit out 5 parts at once for each. The main tie body is made up of 5 pieces that are clipped together with 8 flexible connector pieces, and 5 pattern pieces are designed to clip onto the front of everything. The whole tie slides onto a flexible neckband that is one size fits most. This is an ambitious print, and you need to print either 5 (solid color tie) or 10 ( with a pattern) pieces from the customizer app to make it, and also the neckband and the 8 identical connector pieces which are under the download button. I have actually printed this and it does work. The openscad code that generates the pattern (honeycomb module) is taken from the MakerBot iPhone case( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:40703 ), but all the rest is my own work. Please give feedback and I can tweak the design of the tie to work better! USEFUL TIPS:
-If you don't know what dimensions you want on your tie, you might start by measuring a current tie you own to get an idea what you want
-To print the neckband, set your slicer to zero infill, zero top and bottom layers, and only 1 perimeter. Slic3r gave me good results. There is also a filler piece you need to clip off, you'll see what i'm talking about.
-UPDATE 3/7/12: Now with new neckband option that can be printed on printers with a buld area as little as 100X100 mm. The neckbands have the same total length. Choose the larger one if you have the build area.
-When clipping on the pattern pieces you might need to scrape the clips or the notches to get the right clearances. They can't take too much abuse when being snapped on but work fine once the tie is together. Also, they don't work well if anything is warped, so watch out for that.

title: Bowden mount, optical autolevel and direct drive extruder for the Wilson TS or similar I3 based printer

description.text:
Here are my modified Wilson TS parts. (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:255605). I have done the following modifications:
Replaced Wade type direct extruder with a Bowden extruder to minimize weight on the moving parts. For the mount, I used a design inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:381061, rebuildt it from scratch in solidworks to make even better airflow, and make it fit a E3D V5 chinese clone hotend (which is a pretty good hotend, when treated right). The extruder was inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:245677 rebuildt the base to make it easy to mount on the side of the wilson. My design uses a MK8 drive gear. I also added auto bed leveling inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:263180, also rebuildt from scratch, modified it to use a printed part and a M3 machine screw as rod. It's lighter and easier to make. The system uses an optical switch, and is very accurate indeed. The spring is optional, but if you use one, try to find a soft spring. It does not need to do anything but gently push the rod out. (Gravity will actually do it without the spring).
The design uses a SG90 9G micro servo. They are easy to find, cheap and works very well. Any questions, feel free to ask in the comments.. I will try to answer as soon as I see them. To make the autolevel system work in Marlin, I highly recommend Zennmasters excellent instruction video at http://zennmaster.com/random-things/auto-bed-leveling-for-the-makerfarm-prusa-i3-part-2-setting-up-marlin Here's a video of it autoleveling: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iIzJnyOk_vg Happy modding, dexus.

All parts are printable without support. 0.3 layer height, 3 perimiters and 15% infill on all parts except the extruder part, where I used 0.2 layer height, 40% infill and 4 perimiters (needs to be strong). To assemble you will need: Bowden mount: 4 pcs M3x30 machine screws 4 pcs M3 nuts, The screws that came with the fans or similar (they screw into the plastic). Autolevel rig: One optical sensor (search ebay for optical sensor reprap, see the picture) One SG90 micro servo (ebay) The screws that came with your servo. The optical sensor is made to snap in place, but I added holes to fasten it with two M3X12 screws and M3 nuts. Extruder: 2 pcs binder clip arms from large binder clip (I used a clip measureing 32X20mm) 2 pcs M3X20. 1 pcs M3X8, 2 pcs M3X6, 1 pcs M3X12 + 2 M5X8, with T-nuts to fasten it to the Wilson. See the original author's thing for assembly instructions. To make the Autoleveling feature not retract the probe between positions, and make it lift the probe before retracting it, see this post in the marlin github forum to make the necessary changes to marlin: http://3dprintboard.com/archive/index.php/t-3105.html everything you need to do is in the first post.

comments.text: Well as you offered ... in the Wilson printer thing you said your optical end stop (this thing) was "very accurate indeed". I was wondering how accurate? Did you measure it, and have you compared it with the "traditional" micro switch system? Thanks again.
comments.author: dexus

comments.text:
Well. I don't have the equipment to measure it as accurate as I'd like, but as a general example: In my startup code I have the hotend parked 0.5mm from the bed before starting the print to eliminate oozing before the print is about to start. I have now printed at least 100 things after calibrating, and have yet to experience any deviation from the first print. I also printed a spiral going from the perimeter of the heated bed, to the center, and the line was exactly the same width from one end to the other. So that was way better performance than my last attempt when using a mechanical switch. It is also much softer on the bed, not pushing it down as much, and as such if you have a spring mounted hotbed, you would never experience any flex of the hotbed when leveling.
(I have now actually mounted my heatbed in a fixed position using spacers rather than adjustable springs.. Seemed the logical next step, as the auto bed leveling is compensating for the minimal variations in height.)

title: Vaccum and water attachment for 230mm grinder

description.text:
I bought this angle grinder from Screwfix which was cheap. Reading comments I bought a slightly more expensive diamond cutting wheel which is working great. However it came with no way to attach a vaccum or any holder for putting water onto the concrete when cutting.
It is recommended to use it wet as it produces much less dust, better for the environment and keeps the blade cool. I haven't tried it out yet but it all fits together quite well. Note it does depend on which way the blade rotates and this works for mine.

I planned to use 3mm bolts but I discovered that I had 4mm ones the rights size.  So I drillled out the holes to 4mm (they were supposed to fit 3mm but needed drilling out for 3mm).  
You could improve it by give a bit more space to the bolts so you could use a nut spinner and also move the vacuum tube over to give better access.  However I wanted it roughly where it was which was centered on the blade.  
My angle grinder had a lot of clearance in the cowling around it which made it easy to drill through and bolt on the attachements.  
I haven't tried it out yet.

author: andrewSORG

description.text:
In nature, there are roughly two different types of structural support systems in most animals.  They are either endoskeletal, or exoskeletal.  I think this is also true of our various machines, and it's playing out in DIY 3D printers.
The Mendel represents en endoskelton.  You can imagine putting a skin around it, but largely everything hangs off the 'bones'.
The MakerBot is more of an exoskeleton (at least my cupcake is).  The panels are what everything attaches to.  Without the panels, you don't have a bot.
This thing is a linear slide system that attaches to an endoskeleton.  Similar to the various Z-Riders that are attaching themselves to the MakerBot exoskeleton.  Since it is matched to an endoskeleton, there is no "impedance mismatch" of the design, so there are much fewer pieces.
It's a work in progress.  I'm waiting on a couple of bushings to complete the carriage.  Then I can attach cantilever arms, or whatever.
I thought I'd put it up as it may give others some more ideas along these lines.

1) Figure out the design of an EndoBot
2) Pick a position for your linear slide (typically for a Z-Axis)
3) Print two copies of the endbracket
4) Force fit a 608 bearing into the large holes
5) Cut your various threaded and smooth rods to their proper lengths for your endobot (the rod holding holes are 7.88mm deep. Don't forget this!
6) Assemble everything on your EndoBot
7) Rejoice! The .stl files are for 5/16" smooth and threaded rod. In a few more iterations, I'll upload the .scad file as well for modification.

comments.text: I really like the idea of an endoskeleton. I've thought about making a RepRap using wooden dowels or something of the sorts. It's my belief that the threaded rods and all the misc hardware can be obsoleted by using printed parts without thru holes and carefully cut dowels.

Yet another spool holder!
I failed several printings because the filament was not fed properly. So I decided to build my own parametric spool holder.
You'll need to print 4 parts and to provide 2 nuts, 2 bearings and a length of threaded rod. I used M8 screws and skate bearings but you can choose your own as the design is parametric.

There are several parameters:

  • General:
    Render: allows to choose to compute the spool pulley (0) or the spool holder legs (1) or the complete setup (2).
    Flange_Width: The pulley hexagonal-grip thickness.

  • Spool dimensions:
    Min_Spool_Hole_Diameter, Max_Spool_Hole_Diameter, Spool_Diameter.
    Under_Spool_Clearance: The space between the ground and the spool.

  • Nuts and bolts:
    Axle_Diameter, Nut_width, Bearing_Outer_Diameter, Bearing_Width.
    Nut_Size: The size of the outer nut diameter / circumcircle diameter.
    Axle_Clearance: Adds some space around the axle, 1mm is enough.
    • Print 2 pulleys and 2 legs, clear / cut the prints, hammer the nuts in the pulleys and the bearings in the legs.

However, without the original source files, I was unable to do this.  
There are four files here, one is a complete plate of parts, (apart from the arrow), which is about 135mm x 100mm, the second is a plate of my two changed parts which are also uploaded separately.  
Thank you Tech2C, hope you don't mind me making the above changes to a very elegant design.
